        </exercisegroup>
        <exercisegroup cols="2">
            <introduction>
                <p>Find the difference quotient for each function showing all relevant steps in an organized manner.</p> 
            </introduction>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p><m>\fe{f}{x}=3-7x</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\fe{f}{x+h}-\fe{f}{x}}{h}&amp;=\frac{\left[3-7(x+h)\right]-\left[3-7x\right]}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{3-7x-7h-3+7x}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{-7h}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=-7\quad\text{for $h\neq0$}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>-7</m> for <m>h\neq0</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p><m>\fe{g}{x}=\frac{7}{x+4}</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\fe{g}{x+h}-\fe{g}{x}}{h}&amp;=\frac{\frac{7}{x+h+4}-\frac{7}{x+4}}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{\frac{7}{x+h+4}-\frac{7}{x+4}}{h}\frac{(x+h+4)(x+4)}{(x+h+4)(x+4)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{7(x+4)-7(x+h+4)}{h(x+h+4)(x+4)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{7x+28-7x-7h-28}{h(x+h+4)(x+4)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{-7h}{h(x+h+4)(x+4)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{-7}{(x+h+4)(x+4)}\quad\text{for $h\neq0$}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\frac{-7}{(x+h+4)(x+4)}</m> for <m>h\neq0</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p><m>\fe{z}{x}=\pi</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\fe{z}{x+h}-\fe{z}{x}}{h}&amp;=\frac{\pi-\pi}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{0}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=0\quad\text{for $h\neq0$}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>0</m> for <m>h\neq0</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p><m>\fe{s}{t}=t^3-t-9</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\fe{s}{t+h}-\fe{s}{t}}{h}&amp;=\frac{\left[(t+h)^3-(t+h)-9\right]-\left[t^3-t-9\right]}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{t^3+3t^2h+3th^2+h^3-t-h-9-t^3+t+9}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{3t^2h+3th^2+h^3-h}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{h(3t^2+3th+h^2-1)}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=3t^2+3th+h^2-1\quad\text{for $h\neq0$}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>3t^2+3th+h^2-1</m> for <m>h\neq0</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p><m>\fe{k}{t}=\frac{(t-8)^2}{t}</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>&amp;\phantom{={}}\frac{\fe{k}{t+h}-\fe{k}{t}}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{\frac{(t+h-8)^2}{t+h}-\frac{(t-8)^2}{t}}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{\frac{t^2+th-8t+th+h^2-8h-8t-8h+64}{t+h}-\frac{t^2-8t-8t+64}{t}}{h}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{\frac{t^2+2th-16t+h^2-16h+64}{t+h}-\frac{t^2-16t+64}{t}}{h}\frac{t(t+h)}{t(t+h)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{(t^2+2th-16t+h^2-16h+64)t-(t^2-16t+64)(t+h)}{ht(t+h)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{t^3+2t^2h-16t^2+th^2-16th+64t-t^3-t^2h+16t^2+16th-64t-64h}{ht(t+h)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{t^2h+th^2-64h}{ht(t+h)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{h(t^2+th-64)}{ht(t+h)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{t^2+th-64}{t(t+h)}\quad\text{for $h\neq0$}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\frac{t^2+th-64}{t(t+h)}</m> for <m>h\neq0</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
        <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
                <p>Suppose that an object is tossed into the air in such a way that the elevation of the object (measured in <quantity><unit base="foot"/></quantity>) is given by the function <m>\fe{s}{t}=150+60t-16t^2</m> where <m>t</m> is the amount of time that has passed since the object was tossed (measure in seconds).</p> 
            </introduction>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Find the difference quotient for <m>s</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                   <p><md>
                   <mrow>&amp;\phantom{={}}\frac{\fe{s}{t+h}-\fe{s}{t}}{h}i</mrow>
                   <mrow>&amp;=\frac{\left[150+60(t+h)-16(t+h)^2\right]-\left[150+60t-16t^2\right]}{h}</mrow>
                   <mrow>&amp;=\frac{150+60t+60h-16t^2-32th-16h^2-150-60t+16t^2}{h}</mrow>
                   <mrow>&amp;=\frac{60h-32th-16h^2}{h}</mrow>
                   <mrow>&amp;=\frac{(60-32t-16h)}{h}</mrow>
                   <mrow>&amp;=60-32t-16h\quad\text{for $h\neq0$}</mrow>
                   </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>60-32t-16h</m> for <m>h\neq0</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Use the difference quotient to determine the average velocity of the object over the interval <m>\cinterval{4}{4.2}</m> and then verify the value by calculating <m>\frac{\fe{s}{4.2}-\fe{s}{4}}{4.2-4}</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Letting <m>t=4</m> and <m>h=0.2</m> we have (from the difference quotient):<md>
                    <mrow>60-32t-16h&amp;=60-32(4)-16(0.2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=-71.2</mrow></md>So the average velocity is <quantity><mag>-71.2</mag><unit base="foot"/><per base="second"/></quantity></p>
                    <p>Checking:<md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\fe{s}{4.2}-\fe{s}{4}}{4.2-4}&amp;=\frac{119.76-134}{0.2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=-7.12\quad\text{(Phew!)}</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><quantity><mag>-71.2</mag><unit base="foot"/><per base="second"/></quantity></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
        <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
                <p>Several applied functions are given below.  In each case, find the indicated quantity (including unit) and interpret the value in the context of the application.</p> 
            </introduction>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>The velocity of a roller coaster (in <quantity><unit base="foot"/><per base="second"/></quantity>) is given by <m>\fe{v}{t}=-100\fe{\sin}{\frac{\pi t}{15}}</m> where <m>t</m> is the amount of time (<quantity><unit base="second"/></quantity>) that has passed since the coaster topped the first hill.  Find and interpret <m>\frac{\fe{v}{7.5}-\fe{v}{0}}{7.5-0}</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                   <p><m>\frac{\fe{v}{7.5}-\fe{v}{0}}{7.5-0}=-13\frac{1}{3}</m>. This value tells us that during the first <quantity><mag>7.5</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity> of descent, the average rate of change in the coaster's velocity is <m>-13\frac{1}{3}\,\frac{\text{ft/s}}{\text{s}}</m>.  In other words, <em>on average</em>, with each passing second the velocity is <m>13\frac{1}{3}\,\text{ft}{s}</m> less than it was the preceding second.  We could also say that the average acceleration experienced by the coaster over the first <quantity><mag>7.5</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity> of descent is <m>-13\frac{1}{3}\,\frac{\text{ft/s}}{\text{s}}</m>.</p> 
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p>The average rate of change in the coaster's velocity over the first <quantity><mag>7.5</mag><unit base="second"/></quantity> of descent is <m>-13\frac{1}{3}\,\frac{\text{ft/s}}{\text{s}}</m>.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>The elevation of a ping pong ball relative to the table top (in <quantity><unit base="meter"/></quantity>) is given by the function <m>\fe{h}{t}=1.1\abs{\fe{\cos}{\frac{2\pi t}{3}}}</m> where <m>t</m> is the amount of time (<quantity><unit base="second"/></quantity>) that has passed since the ball went into play.  Find and interpret <m>\frac{\fe{h}{3}-\fe{h}{1.5}}{3-1.5}</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><m>\frac{\fe{h}{3}-\fe{h}{1.5}}{3-1.5}=0</m>. This value tells us that the average velocity experienced by the ball between the 1.5th second of play and the third second of play is <quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="meter"/><per base="second"/></quantity>.  Please note that this does not imply that the ball doesn’t move; it simply means that the ball is at the same elevation at the two times.</p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p>The average velocity experienced by the ball between the 1.5th second of play and the third second of play is <quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="meter"/><per base="second"/></quantity>.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>The period of a pendulum (<quantity><unit base="second"/></quantity>) is given by <m>\fe{P}{x}=\frac{6}{x+1}</m> where <m>x</m> is the number of swings the pendulum has made.  Find and interpret <m>\frac{\fe{P}{29}-\fe{P}{1}}{29-1}</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><m>\frac{\fe{P}{29}-\fe{P}{1}}{29-1}=-0.1</m>. This value tells us that between the first swing and the 29th swing the average rate of change in the pendulum's period is <m>-0.1\frac{\text{s}}{\text{swing}}</m>.  In other words, <em>on average</em>, with each passing swing the period decreases by a tenth of a second.</p> 
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p>Between the first swing and the 29th swing the average rate of change in the pendulum's period is <m>-0.1\frac{\text{s}}{\text{swing}}</m>.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>The acceleration of a rocket (<quantity><unit base="mileperhour"/><per base="second"/></quantity>) is given by <m>\fe{h}{t}=0.02+0.13t</m> where <m>t</m> is the amount of time (<quantity><unit base="second"/></quantity>) that has passed since lift-off.  Find and interpret <m>\frac{\fe{h}{120}-\fe{h}{60}}{120-60}</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><m>\frac{\fe{h}{120}-\fe{h}{60}}{120-60}=0.13</m>. This value tells us that during the second minute of flight, the average rate of change in the rocket's acceleration is <quantity><mag>0.13</mag><unit base="mileperhour"/><per base="second"/><per base="second"/></quantity>.  In other words, <em>on average</em>, with each passing second the acceleration  is <quantity><mag>0.13</mag><unit base="mileperhour"/><per base="second"/></quantity> more than it was the preceding second.  You might have noticed that since the acceleration function is linear, the rate of change in the acceleration is constant.  That is, with each passing second the acceleration <em>actually is</em> <quantity><mag>0.13</mag><unit base="mileperhour"/><per base="second"/></quantity> more than it was the preceding second.</p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p>During the second minute of flight, the average rate of change in the rocket's acceleration is <quantity><mag>0.13</mag><unit base="mileperhour"/><per base="second"/><per base="second"/></quantity>.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
        </exercisegroup>
